indicators.justification:
Law no. 129/2019, transposing European Directives in the field of money laundering, treats in Romania the subject of the beneficial ownership. (1) Public registers showing beneficial ownerships of companies are not fully freely available and in machine-readable formats. In Romania, there are three registers of real beneficiaries, one for the business sector,(2) one for associations and foundations and another for trusts or legal constructions similar to them. The first is operated by the National Office of the Trade Register, the second is operated by the Ministry of Justice, and the third by the National Agency for Fiscal Administration. People who submit requests to request information from the Registers have access only to the requested information, in the online format of the platform. Access to the registers shall be ensured, in accordance with the rules on the protection of personal data:
a) the authorities that have supervisory and control powers, the judicial bodies, under the conditions of Law no. 135/2010, as subsequently amended and supplemented, and the Office, in due time, without any restriction and without alerting the person concerned;
b) reporting entities when applying customer awareness measures;
c) any natural or legal person who can demonstrate a legitimate interest;
d) to any natural or legal person who submits a written request in respect of a trust or similar legal entity holding a shareholding which ensures its control in any legal person governed by private law. 
Sources: 
(1) Law no. 129/2019, transposing European Directives in the field of money laundering, https://legislatie.just.ro/Public/DetaliiDocument/81689
(2) National Office of the Trade Register website, https://www.onrc.ro/index.php/ro/informatii-privind-beneficiarii-reali

Public officials and all civil servants in Romania have to disclose their assets and interests every year. Declarations are to be checked by the National Integrity Agency, but they are also public ex officio. Each public institution needs to upload these declarations. Asset declarations include: (1)
- real estate and any valuable object in their property (cars, art, jewellery etc.);
- any taxable income in the previous year and from this information the National Integrity Agency, in charge of the administrative control of conflicts of interest, or any interested person, can deduce all paid positions in the private sector held by the public official or the civil servant;
- financial investments in companies;
- loans to and from companies or other natural persons;
- gifts, benefits and hospitality with a value over EUR 500, received from private sector entities. Moreover, according to Law no. 251/2004, (2) public officials (including both elected officials and professional public servants) are not allowed to keep gifts received in their official position if their value is over EUR 200. Therefore, the declaration obligations cover as well gifts, benefits and hospitality received in any private context during the period they hold a public office.
Interest declarations include:
- shareholder interests in private companies;
- membership positions in professional organisations or trade unions;
- management positions in private companies or NGOs;
- leadership positions in political parties;
- contracts signed by the declarant, their spouse, parents or children as natural persons or as representatives of a company with any public institution.
Although they do not cover all situations, the fact that declarations of assets and interests are filled in by all public officials (including both elected officials and professional public servants) and that they are publicly available to any citizen, journalist, NGO etc. makes the disclosure policy in Romania relatively strong. However, the number of declarations overwhelms the capacity of the National Integrity Agency to check them. (3) 
Sources: 
(1) Law no. 176 / 2010 on integrity in the exercise of public functions and dignities, for the amendment and completion of Law no. 144/2007 on the establishment, organization and functioning of the National Integrity Agency, as well as for the modification and completion of other normative, https://legislatie.just.ro/Public/DetaliiDocument/121924
(2) Law no. 251 of 16 June 2004 on certain measures relating to goods received free of charge on the occasion of protocol actions in the exercise of their mandate or function, https://legislatie.just.ro/Public/DetaliiDocumentAfis/52934
(3) Transparency International Romania, BICA Research report, 2020, https://www.transparency.org.ro/sites/default/files/TI-Romania_BICA_RO.pdf
